---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Postpartum Hemorrhage" description="Simulation case for postpartum hemorrhage management.">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Postpartum Hemorrhage</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Obstetric</span>
    <h1>Postpartum Hemorrhage</h1>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>⏱ Duration: 50 minutes</span>
      <span>📊 Difficulty: Advanced</span>
      <span>👥 Team Size: 4–6</span>
      <span>🏥 Setting: Labor &amp; Delivery</span>
    </div>
    <div class="tags" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <span class="tag">OB/GYN</span>
      <span class="tag">Hemorrhage</span>
      <span class="tag">Teamwork</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Case Overview</h2>
    <p>
      A 28-year-old G2P2 female, Mrs. Sofia Reyes, delivered a healthy infant via spontaneous
      vaginal delivery 30 minutes ago. The nurse now reports estimated blood loss of 650 mL and
      rising, the uterus is boggy, and the patient's blood pressure is declining.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learners must apply the 4 T's framework (Tone, Trauma, Tissue, Thrombin) to identify the
      cause of hemorrhage, initiate uterotonic therapy, activate the obstetric hemorrhage protocol,
      and manage hemorrhagic shock in a multidisciplinary team setting.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Patient Information</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Name:</strong> Sofia Reyes</li>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong> 28 years</li>
      <li><strong>Gender:</strong> Female</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 72 kg</li>
      <li><strong>OB History:</strong> G2P2, SVD × 2</li>
      <li><strong>PMH:</strong> Iron deficiency anemia</li>
      <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Prenatal vitamins, Iron supplementation</li>
      <li><strong>Allergies:</strong> NKDA</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Initial Vital Signs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>BP:</strong> 92/60 mmHg (↓ from 118/74 mmHg post-delivery)</li>
      <li><strong>HR:</strong> 122 bpm</li>
      <li><strong>RR:</strong> 22 breaths/min</li>
      <li><strong>SpO₂:</strong> 96% on room air</li>
      <li><strong>EBL:</strong> ~650 mL and increasing</li>
      <li><strong>Uterus:</strong> Boggy, does not firm with fundal massage</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul class="objective-list">
      <li>Apply the 4 T's framework to identify uterine atony as the primary etiology</li>
      <li>Initiate first-line uterotonic therapy (oxytocin, methylergonovine, misoprostol)</li>
      <li>Escalate to second-line interventions when bleeding continues (carboprost, tranexamic acid)</li>
      <li>Activate the obstetric hemorrhage protocol and massive transfusion protocol</li>
      <li>Demonstrate effective multidisciplinary team communication (OB, nursing, anesthesia, blood bank)</li>
      <li>Recognize and manage hemorrhagic shock with blood product resuscitation</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Scenario Progression</h2>
    <h4>Phase 1 – Recognition (0–10 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Nurse identifies uterine atony and excessive bleeding. IV access secured, oxytocin
      infusion started, fundal massage performed with transient improvement.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 2 – Escalation (10–30 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Bleeding continues. Methylergonovine administered, tranexamic acid given. Blood
      products ordered. Anesthesia and hematology involved. EBL now ~1200 mL.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 3 – Stabilization &amp; OR Planning (30–50 min)</h4>
    <p>
      MTP activated. Patient stabilized on blood products. Surgical intervention (Bakri
      balloon, possible hysterectomy) discussed. Transfer to OR.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Debriefing Guide</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Were the 4 T's systematically considered during the assessment?</li>
      <li>Was the hemorrhage protocol escalated in a timely manner?</li>
      <li>Were uterotonic medications given in the correct order and doses?</li>
      <li>How was the multidisciplinary team coordinated?</li>
      <li>How was the patient's emotional state addressed during the emergency?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <a href={`${base}cases/`} class="btn btn-primary" style="background: var(--color-primary); color: #fff;">← Back to Cases</a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
